
    THE cops in Limpopo are warning residents to stay safe this festive season. People have been urged to avoid associating themselves with strangers as they might end up losing their valuables, cash or even their lives.Police said residents should be careful at shopping malls not to trust strangers at ATMs, and to always lock their cars properly.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=453355565&t=artid%3d2866f13f-33ca-4380-a05d-a39158b0c1dc%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=453355565&t=artid%3d2866f13f-33ca-4380-a05d-a39158b0c1dc%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>Stokvel groups have been advised to use electronic fund transfers to share their savings, instead of withdrawing large amounts of cash at bank branches. Provincial police commissioner General Nneke Ledwaba has assured the people of Limpopo, including visitors and tourists, that the police will be out in full force to ensure a safe and secure festive season.“People should always keep their personal belongings safe to ensure that criminals do not have a chance to carry out their plans,” Ledwaba told Daily Sun. Limpopo police spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Moatshe Ngoepe said: “People should report any criminal activities in and around their areas or workplaces to the nearest police station.“They can also call 08600 10111 or send an SMS to 32211.”
